subsection.p:
For tangent we have,


                  \tan \left(-x \right) \amp = \frac{\sin \left(-x \right)}{\cos \left(-x \right)}
                                        \amp = \frac{-\sin x}{\cos x}
                                        \amp = -\tan \left(-x \right)


              This means that \tan x is an odd function, and its graph is symmetric about the origin.  A more complete graph of the tangent function is shown in . The graph shows that the period of the tangent function is \pi.  The concept of amplitude does not apply to the tangent function since values of \tan x get infinitely large and infinitely small. \\ \\
              We see that the domain of the tangent function excludes the odd multiples of \frac{\pi}{2};  this can be written as x \ne \frac{2k + 1}{2} \pi, in which k is any integer.  The range is all real numbers. As before, since the tangent function serves as an important function in mathematics, we add it to our toolkit and become familiar with the basic shape, intercepts, and asymptotes of its graph.
